f=Engineering/dana/marketplace/database-migrations/SKILL.md · h1:Database Migration Patterns=Safe, reversible database schema changes production systems. **Rail (Security Charter senior skill):** dana *authors* command script below; **the operator executes them**. Any instruction says "run/apply/deploy" means "produce script plain-language summary `migration-discipline`, hand operator." exceptions, mid-incident included. · h2:When to Activate=Creating altering database tables, Adding/removing columns or indexes, Running data migrations (backfill, transform), Planning zero-downtime schema changes, Setting migration tooling new project · h2:Core Principles=**Every change migration** never alter production databases manually **Migrations forward-only production** rollbacks use new forward migrations **Schema data migrations separate** never mix DDL DML one migration **Test migrations against production-sized data** migration works 100 rows lock 10M **Migrations immutable once deployed** never edit migration run production · h2:Migration Safety Checklist=Before any migration handed operator: · h2:Migration Safety Checklist=Migration DOWN (or explicitly marked irreversible), full table locks large tables (use concurrent operations), New columns defaults nullable (never add NULL without default), Indexes created concurrently (not inline CREATE TABLE existing tables), Data backfill separate migration schema change, Tested against copy production data, Rollback plan documented · h3:Adding a Column Safely=`-- GOOD: Nullable column, no lock \· ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN avatar_url TEXT; \·  \· -- GOOD: Column with default (Postgres 11+ is instant, no rewrite) \· ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN is_active BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT true;` · h3:Adding Index Without Downtime=`-- BAD: Blocks writes on large tables \· CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users (email); \·  \· -- GOOD: Non-blocking, allows concurrent writes \· CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_users_email ON users (email);` · h3:Renaming Column (Zero-Downtime, expand-contract)=`-- Step 1: Add new column (migration 001) \· ALTER TABLE users ADD COLUMN display_name TEXT; \· -- Step 2: Backfill (migration 002, data migration) \· UPDATE users SET display_name = username WHERE display_name IS NULL; \· -- Step 3: App reads/writes BOTH columns (application deploy)` · h3:Removing a Column Safely=Remove application references first deploy drop column *next* migration. (Django: `SeparateDatabaseAndState` removes model without generating DROP COLUMN.) · h3:Large Data Migrations=`-- BAD: one transaction updates all rows (locks table) \· UPDATE users SET normalized_email = LOWER(email); \·  \· -- GOOD: batched with progress \· DO $$` · h3:Prisma (TypeScript/Node.js)=`npx prisma migrate dev --name <name>     # create migration from schema changes (dev env) \· npx prisma migrate deploy                # apply pending migrations — OPERATOR RUNS \· npx prisma migrate dev --create-only --name <name>   # empty migration for custom SQL \· npx prisma generate                      # regenerate client after schema changes` · h3:Prisma (TypeScript/Node.js)=Custom SQL what Prisma can't express (e.g. `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`): create-only, edit migration SQL manually. · h3:Drizzle (TypeScript/Node.js)=`npx drizzle-kit generate    # generate migration from schema changes \· npx drizzle-kit migrate     # apply — OPERATOR RUNS \· npx drizzle-kit push        # direct push: DEV ONLY, never production` · h3:Kysely (TypeScript/Node.js)=`kysely migrate make <name>   # create migration file \· kysely migrate latest        # apply all pending — OPERATOR RUNS \· kysely migrate down          # rollback last — OPERATOR RUNS \· kysely migrate list          # status` · h3:Kysely (TypeScript/Node.js)=Migration files: always type `Kysely<any>`, never current typed interface migrations frozen time. Don't enable `allowUnorderedMigrations` outside development (schema-drift risk). · h3:Django (Python)=`python manage.py makemigrations                       # generate from model changes \· python manage.py migrate                              # apply — OPERATOR RUNS \· python manage.py showmigrations                       # status \· python manage.py makemigrations --empty <app> -n <desc>   # empty migration for custom SQL/data` · h3:Django (Python)=Data migrations: `migrations.RunPython(forward, reverse)` batched `bulk_update` (e.g. 5000/batch). `SeparateDatabaseAndState` decouples model-state changes database operations. · h3:golang-migrate (Go)=`migrate create -ext sql -dir migrations -seq <name>            # create up/down pair \· migrate -path migrations -database "$DATABASE_URL" up          # apply — OPERATOR RUNS \· migrate -path migrations -database "$DATABASE_URL" down 1      # rollback last — OPERATOR RUNS \· migrate -path migrations -database "$DATABASE_URL" force VERSION   # fix dirty state — OPERATOR RUNS` · h3:golang-migrate (Go)=Paired `.up.sql` `.down.sql` files, sequentially numbered. · h2:Zero-Downtime Migration Strategy (expand-contract)=`Phase 1: EXPAND   — add new column/table (nullable/default); app writes BOTH; backfill \· Phase 2: MIGRATE  — app reads NEW, writes BOTH; verify consistency \· Phase 3: CONTRACT — app uses NEW only; drop old in a separate migration` · h2:Zero-Downtime Migration Strategy (expand-contract)=Timeline example: Day add column deploy dual-write Day backfill Day read-from-new deploy Day drop old column. Sequencing deploys co-owned ops's `release-discipline`. · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Anti-Pattern \| Why It Fails \| Better Approach \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\|-------------\|-------------\|-----------------\| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Manual SQL in production \| No audit trail, unrepeatable \| Always use migration files \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Editing deployed migrations \| Drift between environments \| Create new migration instead \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| NOT NULL without default \| Locks table, rewrites all rows \| Nullable → backfill → constraint \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Inline index on large table \| Blocks writes during build \| CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Schema + data in one migration \| Hard to rollback, long transactions \| Separate migrations \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| Dropping column before removing code \| App errors on missing column \| Remove code first, drop next deploy \| · h2:Anti-Patterns=\| *(VYON)* Agent executes a migration \| Rail 3 violation — halt + escalate \| dana authors, operator runs \| · b:with other skills=**migration-discipline (dana, custom):** METHOD authority reversibility, script plain-language summary format, operator-execution protocol. file supplies tool-specific mechanics only; any conflict resolves migration-discipline., **data-modeling (dana):** decides *what* schema be; file *how change applied* safely., **db-performance (dana):** index decisions originate there; concurrent-build mechanics live here., **stack-profile (dev):** names which tool playbook active business; unlisted tools method-only mode (Postgres patterns expand-contract still apply)., **release-discipline (ops):** expand-migrate-contract phases interleave deploys ops sequences, dana authors., **charter-enforcement (quinn):** Rail scan verifies agent-executed destructive op; migrations appear locked plans author-only steps.